00:00:00.309 --> 00:00:02.100
CHERIE HANNOUCHE: Good
afternoon, everyone.

00:00:02.100 --> 00:00:04.400
And thank you guys so
much for coming out, even

00:00:04.400 --> 00:00:05.860
with the weather.

00:00:05.860 --> 00:00:07.730
My name is Cherie
Hannouche, and I

00:00:07.730 --> 00:00:11.950
work in the education team in
Large Customer Sales for GBO.

00:00:11.950 --> 00:00:15.480
And I am thrilled today to
introduce two-time Pulitzer

00:00:15.480 --> 00:00:19.230
Prize winner, Nicholas Kristof,
and award-winning producer

00:00:19.230 --> 00:00:22.780
and head of Show of
Force, Mira Chang.

00:00:22.780 --> 00:00:26.130
Today we're going to talk a
little bit about their newest

00:00:26.130 --> 00:00:30.090
documentary, "A Path Appears--
Transforming Lives and Creating

00:00:30.090 --> 00:00:33.600
Opportunity," which is based
on the book of the same title

00:00:33.600 --> 00:00:37.349
that Nicholas wrote with
his wife, Sheryl WuDunn.

00:00:37.349 --> 00:00:38.890
So I'm going to tell
you a little bit

00:00:38.890 --> 00:00:40.030
about the documentary.

00:00:40.030 --> 00:00:43.430
We're going to play a quick
clip and then bring them up.

00:00:43.430 --> 00:00:47.980
So the actual documentary
follows advocates and actors,

00:00:47.980 --> 00:00:51.830
including Malin Akerman,
Blake Lively, Jennifer Garner,

00:00:51.830 --> 00:00:57.420
Mia Farrow, Alfre Woodard, as
they travel to Kenya, Colombia,

00:00:57.420 --> 00:01:00.290
Haiti, as well as
the United States.

00:01:00.290 --> 00:01:02.890
And they uncovered different
parts of human rights

00:01:02.890 --> 00:01:05.440
violations and the
effective solutions

00:01:05.440 --> 00:01:08.870
being implemented
to combat them.

00:01:08.870 --> 00:01:11.700
Nicholas Kristof is an
award-winning journalist,

00:01:11.700 --> 00:01:14.760
a recognized humanitarian,
a bestselling author,

00:01:14.760 --> 00:01:17.310
and a "New York
Times" columnist.

00:01:17.310 --> 00:01:20.760
In 1990, he won a Pulitzer
with his wife Sheryl WuDunn,

00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:23.880
for their coverage of
China's Tiananmen Square.

00:01:23.880 --> 00:01:28.070
He won a second Pulitzer
in 2006 for his columns

00:01:28.070 --> 00:01:30.290
on the genocide in
Darfur, that are

00:01:30.290 --> 00:01:32.910
said to have single-handedly
focused Americans

00:01:32.910 --> 00:01:36.650
on the attention and atrocities
committed during that time.

00:01:36.650 --> 00:01:40.170
Nicholas has been credited for
reshaping the field of opinion

00:01:40.170 --> 00:01:42.850
journalism and for
being, and I quote,

00:01:42.850 --> 00:01:46.159
"the conscience of
international journalism."

00:01:46.159 --> 00:01:47.700
Through his writings
and initiatives,

00:01:47.700 --> 00:01:50.480
he's done a lot to shine a
light on gender oppression,

00:01:50.480 --> 00:01:54.240
human rights violations, and
social and economic justice

00:01:54.240 --> 00:01:56.930
around the world, and
call on us to do our share

00:01:56.930 --> 00:01:59.890
to make the world
a better place.

00:01:59.890 --> 00:02:02.740
Mira Chang is a producer,
director, and director

00:02:02.740 --> 00:02:04.970
of photography of
nonfiction content

00:02:04.970 --> 00:02:07.370
for domestic and
international television,

00:02:07.370 --> 00:02:10.060
and several full-length
documentaries, as well.

00:02:10.060 --> 00:02:13.990
Her work can be seen regularly
on ABC, National Geographic,

00:02:13.990 --> 00:02:17.250
A&amp;E, and Discovery, and
she's been nominated

00:02:17.250 --> 00:02:20.620
for several Emmys, as
well as Academy Awards.

00:02:20.620 --> 00:02:24.615
Mira also produced the landmark
four-hour PBS documentary,

00:02:24.615 --> 00:02:28.010
"Half the Sky-- Turning
Oppression Into Opportunity

00:02:28.010 --> 00:02:30.090
for Women Worldwide,"
which was based

00:02:30.090 --> 00:02:31.950
on the bestselling book
with the same title

00:02:31.950 --> 00:02:34.510
that Nicholas and
his wife wrote.

00:02:34.510 --> 00:02:37.560
She's currently heading up the
development at Show of Force.

00:02:37.560 --> 00:02:39.640
And we've got some of
them here with us today.

00:02:39.640 --> 00:02:41.920
So welcome.

00:02:41.920 --> 00:02:45.680
And they are the creative
enterprise behind two PBS

00:02:45.680 --> 00:02:47.970
documentaries with
Kristof, and a number

00:02:47.970 --> 00:02:51.080
of Emmy-winning
projects, as well.

