that can talk to certain change

00:27:09.440 --> 00:27:11.070
that we can make.

00:27:11.070 --> 00:27:15.600
MIRA CHANG: You should talk
to that, from in the book.

00:27:15.600 --> 00:27:20.010
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: You know, some
of the stats that really struck

00:27:20.010 --> 00:27:23.690
me are just about the
cost-effectiveness

00:27:23.690 --> 00:27:25.890
of addressing some
of these issues.

00:27:25.890 --> 00:27:28.704
We tend to think
that it's hopeless.

00:27:28.704 --> 00:27:30.620
And I think that's one
reason why we tune out.

00:27:30.620 --> 00:27:33.240
Maybe one problem of
us as journalists,

00:27:33.240 --> 00:27:34.870
and also the
humanitarian community ,

00:27:34.870 --> 00:27:37.360
is we focus so much on the
problems that we lead people

00:27:37.360 --> 00:27:39.627
to think that all
there are is problems.

00:27:39.627 --> 00:27:40.710
That there isn't progress.

00:27:40.710 --> 00:27:42.180
There has been
progress, and we do

00:27:42.180 --> 00:27:44.720
have some evidence-based
interventions that will work.

00:27:44.720 --> 00:27:47.280
And so one of the things we
emphasize, both in the book

00:27:47.280 --> 00:27:49.940
and in the
documentary, is what's

00:27:49.940 --> 00:27:52.360
called home visitation
programs, which basically

00:27:52.360 --> 00:27:56.630
work with at-risk
parents and at-risk kids

00:27:56.630 --> 00:27:58.820
very early in life,
beginning in pregnancy,

00:27:58.820 --> 00:28:01.660
up to the first
few years of life.

00:28:01.660 --> 00:28:04.690
And it's to encourage
pregnant women

00:28:04.690 --> 00:28:10.360
to try to avoid alcohol,
try to avoid drugs.

00:28:10.360 --> 00:28:15.010
After the birth, think about
if you want birth control, then

00:28:15.010 --> 00:28:18.010
here's how you might go about
getting it for a next child.

00:28:18.010 --> 00:28:19.130
Encourage breastfeeding.

00:28:19.130 --> 00:28:21.970
Encourage talking to a child.

00:28:21.970 --> 00:28:27.110
A child on welfare will
have heard 30 million

00:28:27.110 --> 00:28:31.720
fewer words by age four than
a child of professionals.

00:28:31.720 --> 00:28:33.540
30 million more words.

00:28:33.540 --> 00:28:37.750
And so they begin to
speak at the same time,

00:28:37.750 --> 00:28:41.840
but because of that gap
that child on welfare

00:28:41.840 --> 00:28:45.350
is going to be less
prepared for school.

00:28:45.350 --> 00:28:47.030
The verbal parts of
that child's brain

00:28:47.030 --> 00:28:48.321
are going to be less developed.

00:28:48.321 --> 00:28:49.590
It's a huge impediment.

00:28:49.590 --> 00:28:52.390
And so there are these
home visitation programs

00:28:52.390 --> 00:28:59.610
that coach these parents
on these elements

00:28:59.610 --> 00:29:01.940
of early childhood rearing.

00:29:01.940 --> 00:29:05.000
And the result is
that, even though they

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:09.040
end at-- the one that was
studied most ends at age two.

00:29:09.040 --> 00:29:11.070
By age 15, those
kids are only half as

00:29:11.070 --> 00:29:13.360
likely to have been arrested.

00:29:13.360 --> 00:29:15.500
And because juvenile
incarceration

00:29:15.500 --> 00:29:20.230
is incredibly expensive,
$110,000 a year,

00:29:20.230 --> 00:29:23.190
this program, every
dollar invested in it

00:29:23.190 --> 00:29:25.760
pays for itself
seven times over.

00:29:25.760 --> 00:29:29.140
And so we would not only
be doing a huge benefit

00:29:29.140 --> 00:29:32.010
to these kids and
to these moms, we

00:29:32.010 --> 00:29:35.894
would be saving public
money on a major scale.

00:29:35.894 --> 00:29:37.310
And yet this
program-- it's called

00:29:37.310 --> 00:29:39.310
Nurse-Family Partnership--
it still only reaches

00:29:39.310 --> 00:29:42.470
that 2% of the kids
who need it in the US.

00:29:42.470 --> 00:29:47.190
And that's another example
where poverty is indeed,

00:29:47.190 --> 00:29:49.780
in some sense, about
personal responsibility.

00:29:49.780 --> 00:29:55.230
But that irresponsibility,
in part, is that of society

00:29:55.230 --> 00:30:00.175
and not actually implementing
evidence-based programs

00:30:00.175 --> 00:30:01.550
that would make
a real difference

00:30:01.550 --> 00:30:04.460
and would pay for themselves
multiple times over.

00:30:04.460 --> 00:30:05.960
MIRA CHANG: And
